		<!-- message -->
		<div>Chapter 4: Cont'd<br />
<br />
********************************************************** <br />
<br />
On the other side of Antonica, Suria stood on the deck of a ship as well, an evil grin of triumph and anticipation on her darkly sensuous face. The stench of burning fur and flesh still lingered in the air after their brief stop at the trading outpost in Erud’s crossing. The handful of Kerrans there was swiftly dispatched. They posed no strategic threat, but Suria and Marek wanted to keep the blood lust burning hotly in the troops. A small handful that had been slow to obey in Erudin were left behind to make sure the devastation of the small isle was complete. They would be deprived of further combat for their punishment. It proved to be the most effective kind during times of war as no shadow knight worthy of the name could endure the thought of missing the carnage of battle. <br />
The lights of Qeynos were just visible on the horizon. Her vast army would land to the south of the city and be joined by even more Ogres and Trolls streaming up from the Mountains of Rathe. <br />
“Qeynos doesn’t stand a chance, even if those pitiful good races sent their armies to assist!” Suria thought to herself, her violet eyes glowing with excitement. Her thoughts were interrupted when she caught a small movement out of the corner of her eye. <br />
“Stop hiding like a coward and state your business!” she demanded. <br />
A young dark elf male emerged from behind some crates and nervously approached Suria. He ventured to look up at her then quickly averted his eyes, staring at the deck of the ship. He clearly would have rather been anywhere else just then. In a quavering voice, he said, “I have a message, Mistress. Grim news from Sister Isle. Enchantress Viane has been slain by some powerful, unknown magic and the boat carrying this new threat continues on it’s way to Faydwer.” <br />
He bowed his head in anticipation of the consequences of bringing Mistress Suria bad news. He looked up, nonplussed, when he heard her chuckle. <br />
“She has served her purpose well,” Suria murmured to herself. “They have been forced to show their hand and now we can close the trap, knowing the prey is inside. Soon the best and brightest of those weak races will be no more!” <br />
Suria threw back her head and cackled with maniacal glee. When the laughter died away, she looked down speculatively at the young Teir’dal before her, licking her lips. <br />
“My thanks for such good news, young one. Be in my chambers at midnight. I will have need of you then.” <br />
She turned back to stare at the ocean after he hurried away. A part of the message came back to her, making her frown. “A powerful, unknown magic…hmm. What could this be?” she wondered, and then shrugged. “It makes no difference. I refuse to let it! Victory shall be ours!”</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
